      "reviewer_notes": "Gate 1 (Dead Code): Skipped - deserialize_compressed_g1 is called by verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch (verifier.rs:96-97) and multiple EIP4844 verification functions. Gate 2 (Trust Boundary): Passed - attack path is via P2P network (untrusted). Blob commitments from P2P peers are deserialized without identity validation. Gate 3 (Code Verification): Passed - verified crates/serialization/src/lib.rs:69-81. Code calls G1Point::from_compressed which accepts identity point (0xc00000...0000) returning Some(G1Point::identity()). Test vector verify_cell_kzg_proof_batch_case_incorrect_commitment_659a51e9e8c9643a confirms identity commitment should fail (output: false). No identity validation exists in serialization layer or verify_multi_opening. Phase 03's code reading is factually correct. Gate 4 (Exploitability): Passed - attacker-triggered. An attacker can trigger this via P2P by sending blob with commitment=0xc00000...0000 (compressed identity point encoding). The deserialize_compressed_g1 function accepts this, passing identity point to verify_multi_opening which performs pairing checks without identity validation. Pairing e(O, g2)=1 for identity O allows trivial proof bypass. Gate 5 (Spec Cross-Reference): 01e property PROP-57888860-inv-051 from outputs/01e_PARTIAL_MANUAL_kzg_infinity.json states 'KZG commitment validation must reject the point at infinity (identity element of the elliptic curve group) as an invalid commitment.' Code violates this invariant. Gate 6 (Scope Check): Passed - KZG proof verification for PeerDAS (EIP-7594) is in-scope for Fusaka audit. Severity: Original HIGH adjusted to High. This is a single implementation (rust-eth-kzg) rather than entire network, but enables complete bypass of KZG proof verification for commitments set to identity. Impact is cryptographic proof failure, not network-wide consensus split (would require majority adoption). Rust-eth-kzg client diversity impact applies.",
      "spec_reference": "KZG commitment validation must reject the point at infinity (identity element of the elliptic curve group) as an invalid commitment. A commitment equal to the identity point does not correspond to any valid polynomial and must not pass verification. (01e_PARTIAL_MANUAL_kzg_infinity.json)"
    }
